Four members of the Kemerovo Group detained in Estonia and Spain
According to Postimees, police in Spain have arrested Slava Gulevich, known in the criminal world as Slava Kemerovski.
Gulevich, who was detained in Spain, was arrested with the court's permission.
Yesterday, the court also remanded three suspects held in Estonia.
They are suspected to be members of the so-called Kemerovo crime syndicate, aged between 27 and 57, who are mainly involved in drug offences.
In Mijas, in the province of Malaga, Spain, an alleged leader of a criminal organization was arrested.
In Estonia, three men were arrested as suspects, one of whom is reportedly the leader of a criminal organisation and two of whom are members of a criminal organisation.
The information gathered suggests that there was a clear allocation of tasks and roles within the criminal organisation.
The activities of the criminal group were aimed at committing drug offences and thereby earning criminal proceeds,' commented the head of the pre-trial proceedings in the criminal case, State Prosecutor Vahur Verte.
"We do not rule out that the number of suspects in this criminal case will increase", the prosecutor added.
These are people who have previously come to the attention of law enforcement authorities, some of whom have been convicted of drug offences.
Verte emphasised that cooperation with Spanish counterparts has been important throughout the investigation.
"International cooperation has become routine for us and this week's operation shows the success of cooperation", commented Prosecutor Verte.
The head of the Central Criminal Police Agency, Ago Leis, said that the arrests followed a preliminary investigation that lasted nearly a year and a half.
"In the first half of the week, we carried out a long-term operation and arrested suspects in Estonia and Spain at the same time", he said.
Mr Le added that officers from the Central Criminal Police had assisted in the arrests in Spain.
For many years we have had good contact and understanding with the Spanish police and Civil Guard.
These arrests are another message to criminals that we can get them on the other side of Europe,' said Leis.
The information gathered so far strongly suggests that while at liberty the suspects may continue to commit new crimes, which is why the prosecution requested and the court approved their arrest.
The man arrested in Spain is awaiting extradition to Estonia.
In the framework of this criminal case, real estate, vehicles and cash have been seized in order to ensure confiscation.
Pre-trial proceedings in criminal matters are conducted by the Organised Crime Bureau of the Central Criminal Police and directed by the Public Prosecutor's Office.
In 2005, the Tallinn City Court convicted Slava Gulevich of extortion and sentenced him to five years in prison.
In the middle of the last decade, Gulevich was considered the second most important man in the Estonian criminal world after the then underworld leader Nikolai Tarankov.
Originally from Kemerovo, Gulevich rose to prominence in the Estonian underworld in the early 1990s when he began to engage in extortion in Tallinn.
He allegedly collected taxes from taxi drivers and prostitutes working at various hotels, and he charged businessmen a monthly roofing fee.
International joint operations, confiscations of proceeds of crime and final court decisions confirm the effectiveness of the fight against organised crime.
For example, the recent judgments in the case of the so-called 'Dikaev criminal group', where eight defendants were acquitted and EUR 80 000 in criminal proceeds were confiscated, or the judgement against nine persons that Igor Aleynikov created a criminal group in 2006 to engage in the illegal trade in contraband cigarettes and to commit crimes related to human trafficking in Ida-Virumaa and southern Estonia.
The amount of confiscated proceeds of crime is nearly EUR 71 500.
The daily exchange of information between police officers and their foreign counterparts, the exchange of evidence between prosecutors and, where necessary, joint operations in any EU country have ensured the success of these criminal cases.
A civil rights group is warning against travel to Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black travelers to Missouri of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The NAACP Missouri Travel Advisory, which is in effect through August 28, 2017, urges all African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to exercise extreme caution and extreme caution while traveling throughout the state in light of a series of racially charged incidents that have recently occurred across the state and have been reported here".
According to the NAACP, the group was prompted to issue the travel warning by a recent Missouri law that makes it harder to win discrimination lawsuits and by the fact that minorities are disproportionately targeted by state law enforcement.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They are pulled over because of the color of their skin, beaten or killed", said Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri chapter of the NAACP, in The Kansas City Star.
"We've never had so many complaints before".
This is the first such warning the organization has issued for a U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as racial slurs directed at black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died earlier this year under suspicious circumstances after he ran out of gas driving across state lines and Missouri State Police took him into custody without charging him with a crime.
In addition, the memo cites a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General showing that black drivers in the state are 75% more likely to be pulled over than their white counterparts.
"The purpose of the notice is to make people aware and to warn their families, friends and co-workers of what may happen in Missouri", Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared, whether that means bringing bail money or notifying relatives that they're crossing state lines".
According to the most recent data from the FBI's Hate Crimes Reporting Program, Missouri documented 100 hate crimes in 2015, which puts the state 16th in the nation for such violations.
The travel warning is also in response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder to sue a company for discrimination in housing or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel advisories for Texas and Arizona after those states passed immigration laws that required local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations, because the ACLU said it increased racial profiling.
Usually, travel warnings are issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently interest groups have begun using the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
Hepatitis: what should everyone know about the different forms of this serious disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different viruses - hepatitis A, B, C, D, and E.
All these viruses cause acute inflammation of the liver tissue.
However, chronic hepatitis B and C, which can progress to cirrhosis and liver cancer, are more costly.
Kuulo Kutsar, an epidemiology adviser at the Health Ministry, says that the symptoms of acute hepatitis are the same in all types of hepatitis - fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, gray stools, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
Hepatitis is also known as jaundice.
In children, hepatitis may be asymptomatic.
The different types of hepatitis can only be identified by laboratory testing.
Acute hepatitis can turn into chronic hepatitis and can go on for decades without symptoms, which means that a person may be unaware of his or her dangerous liver disease.
Kuulo Kutsar highlights the different forms of hepatitis and describes their progression.
Hepatitis A viruses are spread from an infected person to another by eating or drinking contaminated food or water, by having sex, by touching or passing feces from an infected person to food, surfaces, objects, or the mouth, and by taking drugs.
People who are at risk of contracting hepatitis A include family members and caregivers, people with chronic liver disease, people who have sex with people who are infected, men who have sex with men, drug users, and travelers to countries where hepatitis A is common.
Infection can be prevented by vaccination, which is particularly recommended for frequent travellers and those at risk of hepatitis A.
In addition, daily hygiene is important: wash or disinfect your hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before eating.
Hepatitis B viruses are spread through contact with blood from an infected person, injection of drugs, tattooing, piercing, use of blood-contaminated household items (toothbrushes, razors), donor blood, sexual contact with a person suspected of having hepatitis, and from an infected mother to her fetus/ newborn child.
People who are at risk of contracting hepatitis B include injecting drug users, sexual partners of an infected person, men who have sex with men, newborns born to infected mothers, family members and caregivers of sick people, health-care workers, emergency workers and police officers who come into contact with blood and other body fluids, and travelers to countries where hepatitis B is common.
Hepatitis B can be prevented by vaccinating people, especially those at risk, but also those with chronic liver disease, HIV infection, sexually transmitted diseases, and diabetes.
Other prevention measures for hepatitis B include avoidance of needle sharing, tattooing and piercing, use of condoms during risky sex and avoidance of sexual risk behaviours.
Vaccination against hepatitis B is part of the national immunisation programme in Estonia and is free of charge for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are spread through contact with blood from an infected person, injection of drugs, tattooing, piercing, use of blood-contaminated objects, donor blood, sexual contact with a person suspected of having hepatitis, and from an infected mother to her fetus/ newborn child.
People who are at risk of contracting hepatitis C include injecting drug users, sexual partners of an infected person, men who have sex with men, newborns born to infected mothers, family members and caregivers of sick people, health-care workers, emergency workers and police officers who come into contact with blood and other body fluids, people living with HIV, and travelers to countries where hepatitis C is common.
Prevention of hepatitis C includes avoidance of needle sharing, tattooing and piercing, and the use of condoms during risky sex.
There is no vaccine for hepatitis C.
Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which reproduces in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
Therefore, hepatitis D co-infection with hepatitis B or superinfection may occur in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
Hepatitis D viruses are spread through contact with blood and other body fluids, contaminated needles, sexual contact, and, rarely, from an infected mother to her fetus.
People at risk for hepatitis D are chronic carriers of the hepatitis B virus and those who are not immune to hepatitis B.
An effective prevention measure is vaccination with hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects against hepatitis D virus infection.
Hepatitis E viruses are spread by the faecal-oral route through drinking water and food, including the consumption of undercooked meat, fish and shellfish, donor blood, shared needles and from an infected mother to her fetus.
Travelers to countries with a high incidence of hepatitis E can become infected.
Prevention of hepatitis E involves good hygiene: washing or disinfecting hands after using the toilet, before preparing or eating food, and after caring for someone who is sick.
Wash fruits and vegetables before eating, limit your intake of processed meats, fish, and seafood, drink only safe water, and avoid illicit drugs.
