Despite its title, Anne-Marie O'Connor's Lady in Gold: The Extraordinary Story of the Birth of a Masterpiece by Gustav Klimt, Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer delves much deeper into the cultural life of Vienna in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
But even more deeply into history.
Perhaps a sharper blade would have eliminated the overwhelming amount of information, and a narrower subject would have allowed the extraordinary story portrayed in the title to have greater impact.
Today, it is as if there were two books between the covers: The story of Adele Bloch-Bauer, depicted by Gustav Klimt in his painting The Lady in Gold, and a much larger and more comprehensive history book about respected Jewish families and the German occupation and its aftermath in Austria.
The first third of the book takes you to the heart of Vienna's vibrant cultural life, and once in the Austrian capital, you can easily imagine what life was like around the Ringstrasse more than a hundred years ago, or how everyone in the Café Central got dizzy when Klimt walked in.
The concentration of cultural figures was high in one of Europe's richest cities, and seeing a familiar name in a book makes you feel a little more cultured.
On the other hand, the fact that Sigmund Freud worked in a city plagued by incurable syphilis and with the highest suicide rate in Europe does not seem to add anything to the story.
Or maybe it's just that every brushstroke adds color to the cultural life of early 20th-century Vienna.
Dreaming of a trip to the Soviet Union
In the last decades of the 19th century, the Jewish population of Vienna had exploded, becoming the largest Jewish community in Western Europe.
At the turn of the century, nearly 1 in 10 Viennese was Jewish.
Adele's parents were also newcomers to Vienna, but by the time Adele had married twice to the Czech sugar magnate Ferdinand Bloch and posed for Klimt's famous paintings, her father's bank had become the seventh largest in the Habsburg Empire.
But Adele was not attracted to the glamorous life she was leading.
Looking at the Lady in Gold, it's hard to believe that at the end of her life this great lady was infected with socialism and dreamed of a trip to the Soviet Union.
By 1903, when Ferdinand Bloch decided to commission a portrait of his wife from Klimt, he was the hottest new painter in Vienna.
Klimt's commission cost 4,000 crowns at the time, a quarter of the price of a country house in a good location.
The sugar magnate was not deterred by suspicions of a love affair between the artist and the sitter.
As far as Adele is concerned, the only certain fact is that the close relationship between the model and the artist developed during the work continued for the rest of her life.
Anne-Marie O'Connor - "Lady in the gold.
The extraordinary story of Gustav Klimt's masterpiece, the portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer", Varrak 2016, translated from English by Aldo Randmaa.
Shortly before beginning work on Adele, Klimt had visited the Basilica of San Vitale in Ravenna, and scholars believe that it was the brilliant mosaics of Empress Theodora that inspired the artist to paint a golden portrait of Adele as a mosaic.
Klimt exhibited his "Lady in Gold" in Vienna in 1908, and around the same time (1907-1908), another gold painting, "The Kiss", was born.
Art historians could not help but notice the similarity between the two women.
What's Hitler got to do with it?
"I think that in memory of my friend Klimt I owe it to him to make his handiwork available to the public", Adele Bloch-Bauer wrote a few years after the artist's departure (Klimt died in February 1918) to the director of the Belvedere Museum, wishing their family's Klimt collection to go to the museum.
Six years before his death, Klimt painted another portrait of Adele.
Also in her will (Adele died in February 1925), she asked her husband to leave her two portraits and four Gustav Klimt landscapes to the Austrian Gallery.
She left her jewelry to her nieces, Maria and Luisa.
A year after Klimt completed his "Mona Lisa of Austria", 17-year-old Adolf Hitler had tried to enter the Academy of Fine Arts in Vienna but failed the drawing exam.
Although Hitler's later anti-Semitism is sometimes attributed to his being rejected by Jewish professors at the academy, none of his examiners were actually Jewish.
In any case, by 1939, the task of the Austrian Gallery, referred to in Maria's will, had changed significantly - it had become important to find works from Vienna's rich Jewish art collections to please the Nazi Party.
Hitler's personal art collection also included some works from Adele's home, but not Klimt's.
Sixty years after the Nazis looted the art, a ten-year legal battle began between the Austrian government and the Bloch-Bauer heirs.
Let's just say that if you want to see "The Kiss" at the Belvedere in Vienna, you have to go to the Neue Galerie in New York to see Adele Bloch-Bauer's "Lady in Gold".
And read the aforementioned book before going to Vienna.
Even if you don't plan on going to see the Klimts, because at least my emotions after closing the book revolved more around the Nazi and Jewish themes than the $135 million painting and model Adele Bloch-Bauer.
So it's not so much a portrait as it is the story of a family - and a very moving one.
The family tree of the Bauers, given at the beginning of the book, was a remarkable aid in getting our bearings.
