Blocking critics on Facebook - don't run for public office if you can't take criticism from voters
The father of our country knew a thing or two about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't take long for the newspapers to lambast him for everything from domestic policy to his political beliefs.
The criticism, of course, upset him.
But he did not silence his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said that "freedom of speech may be taken from us and we may be led like sheep to the slaughter".
Which brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to work on being more like Washington.
Hogan's people have blocked and deleted at least 450 posts from his official Facebook page.
And earlier this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him over it.
The governor's office dismissed the lawsuit, and online commentary was rife with "Who cares?" reactions.
"It's just Facebook", many said.
But it does matter.
And that counts for a lot when it comes to a man like Hogan.
This is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in an overwhelmingly Democratic state.
His approval rating is the second highest of the 50 governors in the country.
Hogan is not a knucklehead who reacts without thinking.
He's ruled this state with a firm hand and he's stayed true to his principles.
In addition, he has been quite adept at using Facebook as his primary means of communicating with his constituents, such as hilariously showing off his bald head for the first time since his chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people from visiting the governor's page - which is an officially labeled public forum run by staff paid by taxpayer dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it's all too easy to paint a picture of online trolls, spammers, or hate-filled mobs.
The Post interviewed several of the real people that Hogan blocked.
And that's what they are-- real people interacting with their elected leaders-- a teacher, a business owner and a pastor, not Internet trolls.
They all said that their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not obscene at all.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, emphasizing Hogan's Catholicism.
Lakshmi Sarma Raman, a lawyer from Bowie, Maryland, wasn't advocating hate, she was advocating hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that he had not responded to hate crimes or other recent news", she wrote in a commentary for The Post.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people are commenting on the same thing, some people are just going to casually call it a collective effort instead of acknowledging that it's a lot of concerned citizens".
What the governor's office called a "targeted spam attack", others would probably call "public support".
The age of Facebook makes it easy to match messages by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It's much cleaner than it used to be, when you had to send out workers to do the same thing, to collect critical headlines and burn them, or arrest protesters and silence them.
But that's exactly what's happening now, only digitally.
Hogan isn't the first public official to be criticized for cracking down on Facebook and other social media platforms.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have blocked his Twitter feed.
One of the first landmark rulings on the subject was handed down last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris ruled in Alexandria that the chairwoman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment when she blocked a voter from her Facebook page.
In Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also visited the ACLU over its use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
Back in Washington, affordable mail had a similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled and anonymous correspondents lambasted his leadership.
And even then, Washington had to contend with anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to newspapers under such pseudonyms as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, undermining Washington's decisions.
According to historical documents collected by the George Washington Letters Project online, his office was inundated with petitions criticizing his positions on treaties of friendship, commerce, and navigation with Britain.
But he didn't silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and debate are the cornerstones of our country.
And good leadership means embracing it.
At the Renaissance Club, Ronan Rafferty relies on the comfort of his home turf.
Former European number one Ronan Rafferty is looking forward to the comforts of home over the next three days as the East Lothian Renaissance Club hosts the 25th Scottish Senior Open.
The Northern Irishman, who led last year's penultimate round at neighbouring Archerfield Links before falling to Paul Eales, is attached to the new venue and will act as an ambassador for the tournament in place of the club's founder and CEO Jerry Sarvadi.
"I saw the Renaissance Club being built, and now we're going to see it shine in all its glory with this event", said Rafferty.
"The players see the course at its best, it's in glorious condition.
Jerry's done a great job building this place.
He is an avid supporter of the game of golf and takes great pride in what he has accomplished here.
This allows for a great presentation of the trail".
England's Eales is looking forward to defending his title for the first time, although he has won on both the European Tour and the European Challenge Tour during his 32-year career.
"It's a very special feeling", said a Southport player.
"I was unable to defend my title at the Extremadura Open because it was taken off the calendar the year after I won.
It's magical to come back to this neighborhood.
It's a great place to play golf.
I have fond memories of last year, and for me and my wife Sharon, last year's victory was special.
It was a very special time that will always be in our hearts".
Returning to domestic competition is Gary Orr, who joined the Senior European Tour earlier this year when he turned 50.
This is her first event in Scotland since competing at the Aberdeen Asset Management Scottish Open in 2013.
