Poverty and Death in the Goldfields of Indonesia
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use the stove.
He barely even uses the potty.
In a wooden cottage in Enarotali, the capital of the regency of Paniai, in Indonesia's restive Papua province, a housewife places a sweet potato, known locally as nota, directly on the fire.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed from the fire and eagerly chewed with unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the mud floor - he has no furniture - and does his daily household chores there, such as washing clothes in murky water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket serves as a toilet in a room without a roof.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she is not assigned to look after any field.
Polygamy is common here.
But working late can be dangerous - most of the men in the village are unemployed and many of them drink heavily, plus there are soldiers here.
"No one dares walk around the village after five o'clock in the evening", he says.
This is a rare glimpse into life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was incorporated into Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which just 1,026 elderly people were forced to vote by raising their hands in the presence of occupying troops.
A movement calling for independence from Dutch rule quickly turned its fury against the Jakarta government, which still maintains tight control over the region, keeping out foreign journalists and human rights monitors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, leaving the eastern half of the island to the independent nation of Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is as remote as it is desolate - a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital, Jayapura, to Nabire, followed by a sickening five-hour drive in a rented car.
There is no public transportation.
With a population of about 19,000, the town consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and covered with corrugated iron roofs that have rusted to various shades of yellowish-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made the trip, let alone journalists, and hardly any foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the BaBoos of Mee Pago worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
"We were not used to wearing such clothes", says Degei, referring to her colorful handwoven turban, dark blouse, and bright skirt.
"Before that, we only wore leaves on our bodies".
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line and infant mortality and illiteracy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also the gold country of Indonesia.
Just 60 miles from Pania, a mountainous province roughly the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000, is Grasberg, the world's largest and most profitable gold mine, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran.
In 2015 alone, Freeport extracted approximately US$3.1 billion worth of gold and copper from the mine.
In addition, Papua boasts an estimated $78 billion (U.S.) in timber.
But these riches are a source of hardship for the barefoot, since they result from the suffocating presence of the powerful Indonesian military.
A 2005 investigation by The New York Times revealed that Freeport paid approximately US$20 million to local soldiers and military units between 1998 and 2004, including up to US$150,000 per officer.
The baboons' quest for greater autonomy threatens this golden goose and they are treated ruthlessly.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured, and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the mass killings of Papuan hill tribes in the 1970's amounted to genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
The 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Birsbane, 'We are losing everything', includes testimonies of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture (with rape and electrocution particularly common, according to another report), and the brutal suppression of peaceful protests.
"The number of victims is difficult to estimate because these incidents happen every week", says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened further as Papua's natural resources have led to an influx of settlers from elsewhere in Indonesia.
Eighty-three percent of the province's 3.5 million people are Christian, but the demographics are changing with the arrival of Muslim economic migrants from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
In Javanese family restaurants, gado-gado is served with crispy chicken and mixed vegetables, served with peanut sauce.
The locals can't compete with them.
"The migrants started selling chicken and vegetables at the traditional market at cheaper prices than the local farmers", explains 24-year-old Abeth You, who was born in Paniai and moved to the provincial capital, Jayapura, to work.
"As a result, the indigenous Papuan - the Papuan mama-mama [women] - are losing their market share".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised during his 2014 election campaign to address these inequalities and human rights violations in Papua.
The former carpenter won 27 of Papua's 29 constituencies, including Paniai, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and the local people feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice", says You.
In fact, Paniai suffered a recession just two months after Jokowi took office in October.
On 7 December 2014, 11 children were singing Christmas carols around a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle emerged from the darkness.
The frightened children told them that they should turn on the headlights.
According to a local pastor, Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers took offense at their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and witnesses, drunken soldiers chased children and beat them with the butts of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers fired among the children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby election commission building was set on fire, and the next day things escalated even further.
Some 1,000 young Papuan men, women, and children gathered on the soccer field in front of the local police station and military headquarters to demand justice.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance of the Papuan mee pago tribe, which involved running around and imitating the songs of birds.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and soldiers.
