In late July, a car bomb killed at least 30 people in a predominantly Shia neighbourhood of Kabul.
The Taliban claimed responsibility for the attack.
On 31 May, a major bombing in the centre of the city killed more than 150 people - the deadliest military attack in the country since US-led forces ousted the Taliban in 2001.
The violence underscores the precarious security situation in Afghanistan as U.S. President Donald Trump considers whether to increase the number of U.S. troops assisting the country's military and police.
Correspondents say the suicide bombings in Kabul in recent weeks have also led to a crisis of public confidence in the government, its policies and, in particular, President Ashraf Ghani.
