The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) reversed a decision to delay an Obama-era regulation requiring states to limit smog-causing emissions, one day after 15 states sued the agency over the move.
The EPA announced the decision to proceed with "2015 ozone assessment activities" late Wednesday, saying it shows the agency's commitment to working with the states.
"We believe we need to engage and listen to our state partners", EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt said in a statement.
Pruitt had announced in June the EPA's intention to delay the ozone assessment - which measures smog in different parts of the country to determine where levels should be reduced to meet stricter air quality standards - by one year to October 2018.
Fifteen mostly Democratic states joined the District of Columbia in filing a lawsuit Tuesday saying the decision is illegal.
President Donald Trump's administration has attempted to roll back many of the environmental regulations put in place by former President Barack Obama as part of what Trump says is a broader plan to spur economic growth.
