From what parts of the world do people move to Estonia?
Last year, the Police and Border Guard Board (PPA) extended and issued a record number of over 13 000 residence permits to third-country nationals, most of whom travelled to Estonia to work, study or visit family.
For example, while last year 6702 foreigners were granted temporary residence permits, the figure was 4928 the year before.
Officials cannot say how many immigrants will eventually stay in Estonia permanently, but the Ministry of the Interior is preparing such an analysis.
While ten years ago about 500 Ukrainians a year moved to Estonia, in recent years the number has been approaching 2,000.
The number of applicants for residence permits increased sharply during the Ukrainian crisis - 1087 people were granted temporary residence permits in 2014, compared to 675 a year earlier.
According to Statistics Estonia, the number of Ukrainian citizens in Estonia is growing the most - 850 more Ukrainian citizens arrived in Estonia last year than left.
"The Ukrainian community in Estonia has always been large, and because of the difficult circumstances in the country, it is natural for people to look for work and study opportunities in a country where the community and, for many, family already come first", said Interior Ministry spokeswoman Kristin Rammus.
Last year and the year before, the number of Ukrainians granted temporary residence permits was even higher than the number of Russian citizens, although the latter have been granted the highest number of temporary residence permits in ten years.
If Ukrainians come here mainly for work, Russian citizens for family migration.
"Given the historical Russian community here, they are also more likely to have the strongest family ties to people living in Russia", said Helina Maasing, a migration researcher at the National Defense Academy.
"If you look at where Russian citizens who have received Estonian residence permits have moved to, Harju County is right behind Ida-Virumaa", he added, pointing out that about 40 percent of them are married to citizens of the European Union.
Last year, 1,696 Russian citizens were granted temporary residence permits, also a record number.
At the same time, the number of Russians applying to renew their residence permits actually decreased.
"The jump is due to the fact that instead of extending the residence permit, a new residence permit has been applied for permanently settling in Estonia", explained Rammus, a spokesman for the Ministry of the Interior, who said that Russian citizens' interest in the Estonian residence permit has remained rather stable for years.
Foreigners who have lived in Estonia for at least three years can apply for a new residence permit to settle permanently in Estonia from the previous year.
The aim is to encourage people who have adapted to stay.
However, a residence permit for a long-term resident requires, for example, five years.
Due to the new residence permit, the extension of the old residence permit has probably also decreased.
For example, last year 146 Ukrainians who had worked here for at least three years were granted such residence permits.
Now Ukrainians can change jobs and the Estonian state no longer cares whether the salary criterion is met.
This residence permit has become increasingly popular, with gray passport holders (1029), Russians (487), Indians (54) and Nigerians (36) among the applicants last year.
Altogether, 1,968 people received residence permits to settle in Estonia, including 23 Americans, 12 Egyptians, 18 Georgians, and the same number of Chinese.
In the first half of this year, the total number of such applicants has already reached 1269.
In ten years, Nigeria has surprisingly become a country whose citizens are among the most active applicants for Estonian residence permits.
In 2007, three residence permits were issued to Nigerians, compared with 200 last year.
Nigerians come here to study at the universities.
Estonian universities are also popular among Georgians, Chinese and Turks, for example.
The number of citizens from India, Bangladesh and Nigeria has increased largely due to educational mobility.
For them, too, the rule is that where there is a community, it is easier for others to join", added Rammus.
Over the past ten years, two people have moved to Estonia from North Korea, and the same number from Laos and Madagascar.
Ten people have come here from Cuba, 231 from South Korea, 40 from Indonesia and four from Uruguay.
If around 6000 third-country nationals are granted a residence permit each year, this represents around 0,46% of the total population.
Even when EU citizens are included, migration remains at around one per cent", Maasing commented that the figures were actually low.
According to Statistics Estonia, a total of 14,822 people moved to Estonia last year, while 13,792 left the country.
This means that immigration exceeded emigration in the second year.
Most of the emigrants and immigrants are Estonian citizens, but there are more of them among the emigrants.
As a result, the net migration of Estonian citizens was negative by 2,000 people last year.
Estonians migrate mainly between Finland and Estonia.
