New results of age assessment tests for Swedish asylum seekers published
In Sweden a test was administered to asylum seekers in which their age was assessed using a novel medical approach, and the latest results show that more than 80 percent of those tested were judged to be over 18, although not all believe the results to be accurate.
The Swedish National Institute of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) began tests earlier this year.
The tests were designed to provide a more accurate age assessment during the asylum process after the Swedish Migration Board (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to correctly determine the age of several allegedly underage refugees.
The Migration Agency has so far sent 6,880 cases for testing and the Institute of Forensic Medicine has issued a total of 2,481 test results between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were estimated to be 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the Institute of Forensic Medicine estimated that the test subject "may be 18 years of age or older".
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the person was 'likely to be under 18'.
Tests are only used when the age of the person is in question.
According to Johan Göransson of the Institute of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent with those of previous months.
"We don't see a big difference compared to the statistics of previous months, the numbers are quite consistent", he told The Local.
The fact that a large proportion of cases were assessed as being over 18 years of age does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lied about their age.
The institute released the results of 581 tests in May and said that in 442 cases "there are indications that the subject is 18 years of age or older".
But when the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the results of these 581 tests, it was found that in 243 cases the person had directly stated that he or she would turn 18 this year.
This medical age assessment method, which involves taking X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of the knee joints and then having them analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some circles.
One skeptic is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institute, whose work involves evaluating people's biological maturity to determine whether they went through puberty earlier or later than normal.
'I have had reason to think about it and I do not think that the measurement method currently used should be used.
Determining biological age in this way is highly uncertain.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can", he told the Metro newspaper.
But Johan Göransson of the Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: "Generally speaking, the risk of incorrectly categorizing a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk, about 10 percent, occurs when a person is just under 18".
