The electric car revolution is fundamentally changing the demand for metals.
Who are the winners and losers?
Not only will the electric car revolution fundamentally change everything from fuel markets to infrastructure, it will also create new winners and losers in the metals market.
While mining giants like Glencore can say they're winning in one place and losing in another, it doesn't help smaller mining companies.
Today, Glencore makes its money from coal and oil, but in the future, in the age of electric cars, there will be a growing demand for cobalt, lithium, copper, aluminum and nickel.
This year, the stakes for the spread of electric cars have been raised by the decisions of the UK, French and Norwegian governments to ban the sale of new cars using fossil fuels in the coming decades.
Therefore, Volvo has already announced that they plan to abandon the internal combustion engine and Tesla will launch a cheaper Model 3 electric car.
Bloomberg New Energy Finance forecasts that within two decades, more electric cars will be sold than cars using fossil fuels.
"For some metals, this is a game changer", Simona Gambranini, a commodities analyst at Capital Economics, told Bloomberg.
We've already seen a big impact on metals like cobalt and lithium, which have been in high demand for years.
Electric cars contain about three times as much copper as conventional cars, Glencore said.
Even more copper will be needed at loading stations, which Exane BNP Paribas estimates will increase copper demand by around 5% by 2025.
The increase in demand for batteries for electric cars means additional demand for lithium, cobalt, graphite and manganese.
Glencore will benefit from the upward trend in electric cars, from higher copper prices and from being the world's largest cobalt producer, Jefferies Group predicted.
According to this brokerage firm, the other winners in the electric car race are Freeport-McMoRan and First Quantum Minerals.
The market is already reacting to the changing trend.
The price of cobalt on the London Metal Exchange has risen 70 percent this year.
Last year's price increase was 37 percent.
Copper has also risen 14 percent this year, largely because of economic growth.
Glencore's stock jumped 20 percent in London after outperforming rivals Rio Tinto Group, BHP Billiton and Anglo American.
On the losing side are lead companies like Recyclex and Campine, which have to adapt to the new era.
The main end-use of lead is in the batteries that power petrol and diesel car starters.
Electric cars are powered by lithium ion batteries.
"This is a serious risk to steel demand unless it can be repurposed to overcome the drop in demand", said Michael Widmer, head of metals research at Bank of America Merrill Lynch.
The impact of the free-rolling trend is not yet visible in the form of lead price movements.
Lead has risen 17 percent this year, making it the best performing major industrial metal in London.
Investors see problems for the metal far in the future.
"I'm not sure lead is so bad, because cheap oil keeps conventional cars competitive", said Herwig Schmidt, sales manager for Triland Metals, a metals brokerage.
When demand for lead falls, it does so slowly.
Maybe it'll happen like this in about ten years.
In the meantime, stricter emissions standards mean that demand for hybrid cars, which rely on advanced lead-acid batteries for frequent engine starts, will increase, estimates the International Lead and Zinc Research Organization.
Lightweight metals like aluminum are replacing steel because a lighter car can go further with less electricity.
This explains the additional aluminium demand of 1,6 million tonnes already between 2013 and 2016.
This represents 2,7% of the world's total aluminium production.
