Seagulls are howling on the banks of the North Tallinn Stream.
Their melodic competition is a low-revving tractor plowing stripes on the beach.
In fact, it sifts through two inches [7 cm] of sand, picking up marine debris and human waste - bottle caps, cigarette butts, and the like.
People still come to the beach whether the water's warm or not.
When the weather is fine, people are on the beach, and when it is not fine, people are not on the beach", says Aleksandr Usov, manager of beach cleaning for the nonprofit association Haabersti Haldus.
It is 6:30 a.m., and the beach is being swept clean because by 8:00 a.m., the area must be ready for people.
Usov's been at his post since 4:00.
In addition to Stroom, he also keeps an eye on Pirita, Lake Harku, Kakumäe and Paljasaari's Pikakari beach.
The amount of garbage has decreased.
Years ago, it was a lot more.
People now appreciate what is being done for them", says Usov, who has been cleaning beaches for 15 years.
It used to be that when you put something new up, it was broken the next day.
Now they're keeping what's on the beach.
The Cost of a Clean Beach
One of the biggest jobs on Estonian beaches is cleaning up marine debris.
In Pirita, for example, 400,000 tonnes have to be transported during the beach season.
"This is an incredible amount", Usov notes.
The second major category is household garbage, or what people leave behind.
There are eight large dumpsters along the mile-and-a-half [1.5 km] coastline of the Strom River that need to be emptied three times a week.
That's how much trash is generated.
However, colder summers have meant that there is a fifth less rubbish than usual.
The third category consists of discarded items.
They're mostly children's toys.
This time Usov has scooped a dozen model cars out of the sand.
They'll be waiting for their owners on the frames leading down to the beach.
"Usually there are more, but this is a normal catch". The believer knows that soon he will find them again in the sand.
Children come to the beach and take their toys to bury them again in the sand.
The garbage is scattered
Erika Scholler, a representative of Haaberst's administrative services, admits that the sifting of the tractor disturbs local residents.
The noise, which lasts from the wee hours of the night until the early hours of the morning, disturbs the sleep of neighbors.
During the day, the job is impossible.
You have to sift the beach twice in one month.
"If we don't, the city will fine us", notes Scholler.
However, like Pirita, Pikakari and Pärnu, the aim is to get the Ström beach under the international blue flag quality mark.
"Compared to Europe, Estonia has a lot more work to do to maintain its beaches", says Scholler.
We've got more paddles and rocks, and it's harder to sift through the sand.
However, there is less litter on our beaches than anywhere else in Europe.
Hearing about the garbage on the beach, Martin, who lives near the shore of the Strom, involuntarily joins the journalist and the cleanup crew in discussing the current plight of the beach.
In the morning, there's a disgusting picture everywhere.
The problem is birds and bottle pickers who have pulled the garbage bags upside down", reports Martin.
Although it is unlikely that people will be able to change their habits, Martin hopes that the city will do something about the bins, such as putting lids on them to prevent birds from roosting there.
Overall, however, Martin is satisfied with the development of the Strom waterfront.
You can see the city's taking care of it.
With playgrounds, lighted and freshly paved roads, it has become more pleasant.
There was a time when there was only one way to skate", says Martin.
Treasure hunter finds in the Struma: coins, only coins
Taking advantage of the morning calm, 40-year-old Dimitri scours the beaches like a treasure hunter with a metal detector.
He doesn't think he'll find anything of value today or in the future.
The sea gods aren't generous enough.
"I've been working on it for a year, and so far I haven't found anything worthwhile", says Dmitry.
As an amateur treasure hunter, Dmitri keeps some euro coins, bottle caps, and even dangerous nails in his treasure chest, which he later throws away.
There's usually coins.
"Gold, rings, and the like are not usually found", notes the treasure hunter.
The Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that interest rates will remain unchanged, as weak economic growth and easing inflation have dampened speculation about increases.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish as tightening household incomes have put interest rates on hold.
The Bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) policymakers voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25% and fewer members are calling for a hike this month as sluggish economic growth has weakened support for an increase.
In its Quarterly Inflation Report, the Bank cut its growth forecast to 1,7% in 2017 and 1,6% in 2018 and warned that pressure on household incomes would remain as inflation was still expected to rise close to 3% in the autumn.
However, the Bank also indicated that rate increases would be needed over the next few years to contain Brexit-induced inflation and that financial markets may need higher-than-expected increases in borrowing costs.
MEPs also voted to partially reverse the mammoth economic stimulus package triggered by Brexit a year ago.
The Bank will end its term funding scheme, which provides cheap funding to banks, in February, although it has said it now expects a £15 billion increase to £115 billion under the scheme.
In the minutes of its decision on the rate, the Bank states: 'The MPC's medium-term projection of gross domestic product (GDP) remains weak for the foreseeable future, as the difficult situation of households' real incomes continues to weigh on consumption.'
Regarding rates, it was reiterated that 'some tightening of monetary policy' would be needed to moderate inflation, and to a 'somewhat greater extent' than expected by the markets.
The stock exchange is currently forecasting a first increase in the third quarter of next year and a second increase in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any jumps would be gradual and limited.
The Bank's downgraded growth forecasts for this and next year are comparable with the May forecasts of 1.9% and 1.7%.
The Commission's forecast for 2018 remains unchanged at 1,8%.
Following this news, the pound fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound sterling declined by 0.5% to USD 1.31 and by 0.4% to EUR 1.11.
The decision not to make any changes is driven by recent disappointing growth figures, which have dampened growing expectations of recovery - GDP rose to 0.3% in the second quarter from 0.2% in the previous three months.
The Bank says that growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will pick up slightly towards the end of the year.
The bank's latest inflation report gave little cause for rejoicing to households suffering from rising inflation and miserable wage increases, saying that things would get a little worse before they got better.
It added that monetary policy could not prevent a hit to incomes over the next few years, but wages were expected to recover significantly towards the end of the three-year forecast.
The weak pound also stimulates the economy by increasing demand for British products, which partly offsets lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were raised to 0.25% last August after the shock EU referendum resulted in a sudden weakening of the pound.
The Bank estimates that it will probably take four years for prices and the economy to recover fully.
Prior to the Bank's latest decision, there had been increasing calls for an increase in the rate, as inflation had increased pressure on distressed households; in July, three policymakers called for an increase to 0.5%.
Inflation fell to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June, although the bank said this was expected and was expected to rise again in the coming months.
The Bank said that the excess over the 2% target was entirely due to the weak pound.
Andrew Montlake, head of Coreco Mortgage Brokers, said: 'Given the recent fall in exchange rates, it seems that the mortgage market is becoming increasingly competitive again as lenders are hungry for work and hope to end the year on a positive note.
The stock market seems to be particularly favourable to those whose current transactions are coming to an end, as refinancing, often free of charge and at a low rate, has become increasingly popular.'
The NHS is about to prescribe a controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people.
Patients will have access to 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment from September, following a high court battle over whether the NHS should fund the drug.
NHS England has announced that the NHS is now making available to an estimated 10,000 people in an initial three-year clinical trial a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, given before sex, which has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by around 86% in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the clinical trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a High Court ruling last year that the NHS was able to pay for PrEP, despite its own claims that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
Simon Stevens, chief executive of NHS England, welcomed the move, announced on Thursday, as a "new large-scale intervention", while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) described it as a "turning point".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to start enrolling people.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medicines taken before sexual activity to reduce the risk of becoming infected with HIV.
The results of clinical trials show that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in people at risk.
Taking PrEP before sex means that you have enough of certain medicines in your body to prevent HIV infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sexual activity.
Eligible candidates for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people whose HIV-infected partners are not receiving treatment.
Clinics will identify eligible people who are willing to participate in a clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people and those whose HIV-positive partner is not receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen their GP there can also register with a local sexual health clinic participating in the scheme.
The programme costs £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to receive the drugs this week after an international tender process.
The aim of a clinical trial is to assess the real potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence about who the medicine is intended for and how it is consumed and used in the wider context.
Stevens said: "This new large-scale intervention should complement and amplify the widespread and increasingly successful fight against the spread of HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of fighting one of mankind's greatest health challenges".
Deborah Gold, executive director of NAT, said: "This is a watershed moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted to those who need it and are at risk, has the potential to transform the HIV epidemic in England.
From September, people at high risk of HIV in England will have access, through this NHS-funded clinical trial, to a powerful new tool that is individually manageable and not dependent on negotiation with a partner, improving many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement".
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: "The priority now is to ensure that a clinical trial is rapidly rolled out across the country and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that we've secured the PrEP trial drug, we're on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV.
Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: "The start of the PrEP clinical trial is very welcome and long overdue after months of delays and government foot dragging.
The evidence shows the difference this medicine can make in preventing HIV and stopping the spread of this life-changing infection.
This clinical trial brings us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the clinical trial be rolled out nationally as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and bring us one step closer to halting the spread of HIV in the community".
The price of electricity increased by 12% in Estonia and decreased in Latvia and Lithuania.
In July, the difference in the day-ahead market price of electricity between the price areas of Estonia and Latvia and Lithuania decreased to EUR 1,94, compared with EUR 7,71 in June this year, Elering reported.
The main reason for the price difference is the breakdown of the Lithuanian-Swedish connection.
In Estonia the average price of electricity on the stock exchange last month was 34.33 euros per megawatt-hour, up 12 percent from June.
In Latvia and Lithuania, the price fell by 5% to EUR 36,27 per MWh.
In Finland the price was EUR 34,17 and the system price of Nord Pool EUR 26,37 per MWh.
Prices increased by 12% and 7% respectively.
Between Estonia and Finland, electricity flowed 75 percent of the hours last month to Estonia and 16 percent of the hours from Estonia to Finland.
For the remaining 9% of the hours, there were no next-day transactions between the two countries.
Between Estonia and Latvia, electricity flowed from Estonia to Latvia 99% of the time and full transmission capacity was used 73% of the time.
On the basis of transactions on the last trading day of July on the Nasdaq OMX market, the electricity exchange price could be around EUR 34/MWh in August and EUR 37/MWh in September.
The price of carbon dioxide, which affects the price of electricity generation, increased last month and traded between EUR 5,04 and EUR 5,47 per tonne.
High-rise living - a mezzanine and clever design tricks have transformed this small Earls Court flat into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker who is a passionate property developer, exchanged her large Knightsbridge home for an Earls Court apartment in 2014.
It's on the first floor of Queen Anne Terrace, and the fact that Joanne hasn't packed her bags and sold the apartment is a tribute to the new design.
"Before that, I lived with my ex-partner in Knightsbridge on a much larger property", said Joanne.
"I was looking for something that would match my price.
I was shown this flat in Earls Court and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with it and made an offer the same day".
Since our first visit, this 93,000-square-foot [93 sq m] apartment has been completely renovated.
Originally a one-bedroom apartment with a complicated layout - you had to walk through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - Joanne wanted to add storage and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands", he said.
She hired Erfan Azad from Notting Hill-based architecture and design studio Duck & Shed to take advantage of the 3.8m high ceilings and create a home that would not just be a development but a place for Joanne to live.
The ceiling wasn't high enough to add two rooms on top of each other, so the architectural challenge was to create a mezzanine where you could stand up.
Erfan had to get creative.
"The metal structure is quite complex", he explains.
"We had to rearrange the rooms so that they were on top of each other without bending.
It was not just a question of building a platform. We used a steel structure so that both the upper and lower spaces were the right height".
This arrangement allowed Erfan to create two full-height rooms in a room, one on top of the other, with plenty of dramatic elements.
Halfway up, an antique Retrouvius window with a copper light overlooks the glamorous living room below.
Reflective gold furnishings, silver accents, and retro lighting by Serge Mouille enhance the style of the room.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding theatricality, spaciousness and light saturation.
Mirrors have been added at each end of the short corridor to make it appear longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored back wall creates the illusion of a window into another room.
At the entrance, a mirrored cabinet provides storage for all of Joanne's cutlery and glassware.
Adding to the charm of the living room is the ability to close off the kitchen area when not in use, creating the illusion of a more glamorous space.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
What is unique about this kitchen, however, is that it has a garage-type lifting door.
"It took some design work", explains Erfan of the steel-reinforced MDF door.
"It has a counterweight, which makes it slide very easily when you push it up".
Thanks to clever use of space and storage, Joanne now has 16 square feet [16 sq m], an extra bedroom, and a better floor plan.
"After all, it is the floor space that you are selling - or that gives the property value", says Erfan.
"Real estate agent walks into a room wearing an outdated uniform and makes calculations based on floor space".
Here they have been able to increase the floor space while using quality materials that add luxury to the space.
"Materials are what you touch, and they help you form an emotional attachment to your home", says Erfan.
"You don't fall in love with the wiring in the wall.
It's important, but it doesn't make the heart sing".
It shows that good design and increased floor space can transform a fairly ordinary apartment into something amazing.
In fact, they may even make you want to stay, as happened to Joanne.
The protagonist, Dane Jensen, is a Chicago skyscraper bounty hunter who competes with a colleague for a promotion.
All that matters is the amount of money earned, which makes all ethics obsolete.
A man sees his wife and three children only early in the morning and late at night.
For the first half of the movie, I find myself thinking, this is the corporate version of "House of Cards" -- even Kevin Spacey and Gerard Butler sound alike.
As the film progresses, however, the more the moralizing intent of the filmmakers becomes apparent.
A life-changing experience for the protagonist is his son's cancer diagnosis.
Now you have to choose between work and family.
A son who dreams of becoming an architect takes his father on walks to the top of Chicago's skyscrapers and makes him think about the things that really matter, like faith, goodness, love... not even missing the Twin Towers disaster.
After the third scene, in which the son opens his father's eyes, it seems that the filmmakers are determined to make the audience cry, for even the most hardened spectator cannot hold back the tears at the sight of a dear boy suffering from cancer.
When the son falls into a coma and his situation seems almost hopeless, the father finally realizes the morality of his work and does a good deed for an old man looking for work.
Now I'm betting in my mind that if the movie has a happy ending, I'll reward my insight with coffee after the movie, but if I'm wrong, I can credit the writer with at least one surprise.
For a moment, I think I'm going to miss my coffee when my wife calls Dane from the hospital and he races down the hall in slow motion towards the palace.
The son, however, has miraculously recovered, and although his father has just lost his job, this too is a positive development, since he now has time to care for the family.
I can feel pretty good about myself. I can predict the end of American drama pretty good.
To tell you the truth, the film is well constructed, all the elements are there.
You can cry, you can laugh, the actors are good and the moral is beautiful: money is not the most important thing in life.
I'm sure this movie will bring in a lot of money.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the president's media consumption.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it for real.
In that case, he'd be the first.
Politico reports that the White House's new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information, including news, to President Trump in hopes of keeping him in line.
Here's an excerpt from reporter Josh Dawsey:
"When new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met with senior officials on his first day in office, he brought up a key problem in President Donald Trump's White House that he planned to fix - bad information getting into the president's hands.
Kelly told officials that information had to flow through him, whether on paper or in meetings, because the president would make better decisions if he was given good information".
Kelly's diagnosis seems perfectly logical, but others have tried and failed to tame Trump by monitoring his media consumption.
President Trump's relationship with television goes back decades, and even now that he's in the White House, his TV habits haven't changed.
"If candidate Trump was upset about dishonest media coverage, it paid him to show that he was also being covered honestly by influential outlets", former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
Politico's Tara Palmer wrote at the time that "six former campaign workers say the key to controlling Trump's Twitter habits is to ensure that his personal media consumption includes a steady stream of praise".
All right, you know what?
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habits were ever "under control" is ridiculous.
Maybe these campaign workers know something the rest of us don't - that Trump's tweets would have been even more inflammatory without their interference.
We'll probably never know about the tweets that Trump didn't post.
If his assistants managed to get him out of trouble even a few times, their efforts were worthwhile.
But no one has been able to stop Trump from consistently creating controversy.
Part of the problem is that in a White House of competing cliques, people are almost exclusively trying to advance their own interests by feeding Trump material that supports their worldviews, but may not always be credible.
In May, Politico reported on the tendency of advisers to feed the president information of questionable strategic value.
One example, described by reporter Shane Goldmacher, is this:
"Current and former Trump aides say Trump can react to negative press, especially damaging leaks, with an explosive obsession to find their source.
This was the case in late February, when someone gleefully handed the president a printed copy of an article on the Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson's GotNews.com website that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the "source of multiple leaks" to the White House.
It doesn't matter that Johnson has been permanently banned from Twitter for defamation, or that he offered no concrete evidence, or that he has made and retracted false accusations in the past.
"Trump read the article and started asking his staff about Walsh".
Goldmacher added that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Chief of Staff Rob Porter "have tried to establish a system for managing and documenting the documents that reach Trump".
How'd you manage that?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do exactly the same thing.
He may prove to be a more effective leader than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his aides are still competing for influence.
These immutable factors make Kelly's mission very difficult.
Street musicians who come to the capital from abroad do not hesitate to ask for permission to perform.
There are many foreigners playing music in the center of Tallinn.
Those interviewed by the Evening Post admitted that they were playing in the Old Town without permission from the city council.
The first thing we found near the gates of Viru were three street musicians who had brought the same number of dogs with them.
It was obvious that the musicians, with their Rastafarian hats and tattered clothes, were backpackers who needed a shower.
Despite her appearance, the only woman in the group played the accordion to a cheerful rhythm while a man next to her juggled three balls, beckoning passersby closer.
A third man was sitting next to them on a backpack, smoking a homemade joint in peace.
The three dogs were undisturbed by the passing crowd.
Noemi, who played the accordion, and Bob, who juggled balls, said that they performed on the streets for fun as well as for money.
The purpose of the performance was to raise money for a ticket on a ship leaving for Finland that evening.
When asked if they had asked the city for permission to play music in the Old Town, Noemi and Bob shook their heads.
First of all, we didn't know.
Second of all, we never stay in any one city for more than a day or two, and we're usually given permits for a month or so.
There's no point in paying for it", Bob explained.
When we returned to the gates of Viru some 20 minutes later, we saw that two women were chasing the musicians away.
The group moved with their backpacks and dogs to the intersection of Viru Center to try their luck.
Three young Polish men also performed on Viru Street. One played the violin, another the clarinet, and the third carried an electronic piano.
"We are here to entertain people, to spread music and joy, and to earn money for fuel and living expenses", explained Mivosh, a pianist in the trio.
According to Mivoshi, they are aware that to perform, they need permission from the city government.
"Of course we don't have it", he joked.
But we hope that if people enjoy our music, then there's no problem.
Of course, if the police come, we'll go somewhere else, but we have to try", he added.
In July, Eesti Pank purchased EUR 149 million of bonds under the public sector purchase programme of the euro area central banks, bringing its total bond portfolio to EUR 4.36 billion.
The ECB does not disclose further details of the purchases.
Hardo Hansson, Governor of Eesti Pank, has previously explained in reply to a parliamentary question that the Eurosystem CBPP comprises three different purchase programmes: covered bonds, asset-backed securities (ABS) and public sector purchase programmes (PSPP).
The central bank buys bonds from the market to encourage investors who have sold the bonds to invest elsewhere.
Purchases have the effect of reducing the yield on lower-risk assets, which provides an incentive for investors to take on more risk.
As a general rule, each central bank buys its own government bonds under a public sector purchase programme and no other government bonds are purchased.
Since no bonds have been issued by the Estonian State, Eesti Pank will make so-called replacement purchases within the volume allocated to them.
Replacement purchases are also undertaken by central banks in countries where the supply of bonds under the purchase programme is limited.
According to Mr Hansson, Eesti Pank generally purchases bonds issued by European institutions, such as the European Financial Stability Fund and the European Investment Bank.
Eesti Pank has been purchasing bonds under the APP since March 2015.
In the meantime, Elering bonds were also purchased, but as of June 2016 Eesti Pank no longer purchases Elering bonds.
Since June, both Elering and Eesti Energia bonds have been purchased by the Bank of Finland on behalf of the euro area central banks.
The travelers bypass the ditch and return to the "millionaire's quarter"
Some of the wealthiest homeowners in the West Midlands are once again locked in a fierce battle with determined squatters who have defied the council's moat to win back the land away from their villas.
The travelers have parked their 20 trailers in a field near Solihull Street, dubbed the rich man's "millionaire's quarter".
They've returned with an army of horses, children and trucks after being driven out in May, undisturbed by the ditch the council dug to prevent their invasion.
The tactical team found a weak spot in the perimeter, squeezing their vehicles through an unblocked section that was left open to foot traffic.
Angry pot residents have cursed Solihull council, saying the council is "useless in dealing with the problem".
One anonymous resident said: "They moved in on Monday night after being evicted from Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by.
The council needs to be shamed into action because they're useless at dealing with the problem.
The Travelers were there in May, they were driven out, and now they're back again.
There were more last night, probably more tonight".
He added: "Birmingham Council knows how to deal with this sort of thing by getting long fences to protect their parks.
I live on Streetsbrook Road and I'm not happy that I have to keep paying council tax when the council can't even prevent this sort of thing".
A local resident, who also wished to remain anonymous, said: "It's ridiculous, we just saw the last of these travelers leave, and already there's another attack.
This time the number has increased, and even a horse has been seen in the grass".
A Solihull council spokesman said: "We are aware of an unauthorised encampment on land near Streetsbrook Road and are working with Solihull Police to take the necessary legal action to move them as quickly as possible.
It is very helpful in gathering evidence if as many local people as possible report any antisocial or criminal behaviour to the police by calling 101.
This will help to paint a picture for the court when we present the case to them".
Minister of Culture Indrek Saar will be among the guests of the weekend festival, and he is pleased that we have been able to bring the world's top names to Estonia.
When asked why the Weekend festival is so important to Estonians, Saar replies that it should be asked to all those who enjoy the three days of the festival to the fullest.
However, he admits that real experts in their field have arrived in Pärnu.
"Looking at the level of artists that have been brought to Estonia, the absolute top names of this music genre are brought home - this does not often happen in our region", says the Minister of Culture.
Which artists perform at the festival but Saar himself is the most talked about?
I consider myself a relatively old person, and for old people like me, certainly one of the most experienced artists is Armin van Buuren, who performed last night.
Judging by the way he spins his record, all of us have done it at one time or another", he says.
Yeah, but he's got a bunch of other names, like the Chainsmokers, Deadmau5, Knifeparty.
And, of course, our Estonian heroes, starting with NOËP.
In fact, this concentration of well-known names is very high", he says.
