Audi renews up to 850,000 diesel cars amid criticism from carmakers
The day before Audi's announcement, BMW said it would offer the software upgrade to more than 350,000 vehicles.
According to the chairman of BMW, the company believes that "there are smarter options than driving restrictions", referring to European cities, including BMW's home city of Munich, which have considered banning or restricting diesel vehicles.
Daimler announced Tuesday that it will retrofit three million Mercedes vehicles in Europe to reduce emissions from diesel engines.
None of the companies described these actions as recalls.
European car manufacturers have aggressively promoted the use of diesel vehicles in Europe and the United States to help comply with regulations on carbon dioxide emissions.
However, nitrous oxide from diesel engines is considered a carcinogen and can cause asthma.
It will also increase the cost to car manufacturers of installing equipment to neutralise emissions from diesel vehicles, making it difficult to keep the price of cars competitive.
While German automakers are under intense scrutiny, Chancellor Angela Merkel's government has also been accused of pandering to powerful automakers and ignoring warning signs.
Companies are trying to avoid repeating the mistakes of Volkswagen, which concealed the use of so-called defeat devices that allowed the emissions to be adjusted to meet regulations while the car was being tested, only to withdraw under normal driving conditions.
Several Volkswagen executives have been indicted in the United States and others are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
Last month, the former head of the thermodynamics division of Audi's engine development division was arrested in Germany.
Former director Zaccheo Giovanni Pamio is Italian and therefore not protected against extradition and can be tried in the United States.
Earlier this year, Audi was drawn into a criminal investigation into Volkswagen in Germany when authorities accused it of installing the Audit system to evade European emissions standards, expanding an investigation that had previously focused on the United States.
Audi's involvement in the investigation could be a major blow to Volkswagen - the luxury carmaker generates a disproportionate share of Volkswagen's profits.
Flags of the European Union will be purchased for Estonian schools at a cost of EUR 20 000.
The Ministry of Education intends to buy European Union flags for Estonian schools by 1 September to mark the Presidency.
A total of 570 educational establishments will display the flag of the European Union, measuring 105 by 158 centimetres.
The flags are designed to be displayed indoors and must be printed with high-quality printing technology indoors, including with a tunnel attachment, reports the ERR news portal.
The sign on the flagpole reads: "A gift to Estonian schools to commemorate Estonia's first presidency of the Council of the European Union.
The estimated cost of 570 flags is around EUR 20 000 according to the Ministry of Education, or EUR 35 per flag.
Murder of journalist highlights growing threat in Mexico
The staff of the weekly newspaper Riodoce usually gathers on Wednesdays to review plans for covering the latest chaos in Sinaloa state, which has been plagued by organized crime, corrupt officials and an ongoing drug war.
But today, they have gathered in the shadow of a personal tragedy to discuss their safety.
They are told that it is important to change their routine.
Two elderly journalists debate whether it is safer to bring their children to an office that was bombed in 2009 or to leave them at home.
Security experts have written three words on a board at the front of the room: "enemies", "neutrals", "allies".
They ask reporters to provide names for each column - no evidence needed, just impressions and hunches.
Suspected government or cartel employees include drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen and journalists - a list of villains that makes reporting on the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
There is no respite from the violence, and as more bodies pile up across the country, more of them are journalists - according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012, at least 25,589 journalists have been placed under state protection after attacks and threats, and so far this year, at least seven journalists have been killed in seven states.
Among the latest to die is their editor and inspiration, Riodoce co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist", wrote Valdez in one of his many books on drug violence.
His absence is deeply felt, although his presence can be felt everywhere - on the facade of the Riodoce building hangs a large picture of Valdez pointing his middle finger with the words "Justice" and two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts depicting his smiling face with glasses or his characteristic Panama hat.
The meeting takes place less than two months after her death, and the reporters discuss their shared trauma, their nightmares, their insomnia, their paranoia.
Although a separate state prosecutor's office was established in 2010 to deal with journalists' cases, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, only two cases have been prosecuted.
As with most murders linked to drug trafficking and organised crime, which number in the thousands each year, the killers of journalists rarely face justice.
The editorial staff of Riodoce continues to cover the violence in Sinaloa, although their hearts are broken and the landscape is now even more dangerous.
Without information about the killers and justice, Ibarra said the security meeting would be of little use.
"It's very silly to waste your time in this meeting", he says.
"Until you know the reason, you distrust everyone".
Valdez left the Riodoce offices in Culiacan, the state capital, on the morning of May 15.
He only managed to drive a few blocks before two men in a red Toyota Corolla stopped him, forced him out of the car, and shot him 12 times, presumably because of the newspaper's name, which translates to "the twelfth river".
The gunman drove off in Valdez's car and crashed nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He left behind a wife and two grown children.
Word travels freely in Culiacan.
But for the most part, Valdez has remained silent.
Since Guzman's arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has been one of the country's bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions fight to fill the power vacuum.
It does not matter that a person or several people are gunned down each day on the streets of Sinaloa or that the cemeteries are filled with lavishly decorated double mausoleums of drug lords larger than the homes of many living people.
Let's forget for a moment that peacetime refers to when a coastal state with valuable ports and drug routes into the United States is run by a single cartel.
Despite all this, and the fact that Valdez was fully aware of the risks involved in his work, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, co-founder and director of Riodoce, feels immense guilt for not having been able to protect his friend.
He believes two mistakes contributed to the killing.
The first of these was the publication in February of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the head of a rival warring faction of the cartel.
This piece may have angered the sons - suspected gang members bought up all copies of the publication as soon as they reached the newsstands.
The second mistake was that Valdez was not forced to leave the country for his own safety after a raid on another newspaper covering the same story.
Valdez was a legend both in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is seen as a turning point in the violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would be around forever.
He was working at the newspaper Noroeste in 2003 as a veteran reporter when he teamed up with five colleagues to create Riodoce by selling $50 shares.
Bojorquez said that in Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without dealing with the drug problem".
In time, the paper gained a reputation for bold and honest reporting, and sales and advertising increased.
Reporters enjoyed publishing powerful investigations without fear of censorship, and readers were captivated by the printed page, where they could read stories that no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after Riodoce was founded, the newspaper won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Prize for its coverage of Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists (CPJ) for his courage in following the Mexican drug cartel wherever it leads.
He freely admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to go on living", he said as he accepted his AAC award.
In an interview with Rompeviento TV last October, he said that drug trafficking is a way of life in Sinaloa.
"You have to embrace the responsibility that comes with being a journalist - the alternative is to play dumb.
I don't want to be asked what I did in the face of so many deaths or why I didn't say what was happening".
The Riodoce collective misses Valdez, a joker who cursed like a sailor, a friend who gave hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They relied on his routine.
He always wore his hat.
He would go to the El Guayabo bar across the street from the office and always sit at the same table.
Now they wonder if her love of routine was her undoing.
His death has also made them question how best to do their jobs and stay alive.
"They don't like it when you mess with their women, their children, their legitimate businesses, their secret landing sites used to transport drugs".
"You're not supposed to touch those things", Bojorquez said.
The result, even in the best of times, is intense self-censorship and self-preservation.
Trusting your instincts.
If it smells fishy, stay away.
According to Andrés Villarreal, editor of Riodoce, the problem is that "the sense of smell can be deceived . . . and that is what happened to Javier".
He and others say the old rules no longer apply in Sinaloa, just as they don't in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt public officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
Cell phones were suddenly not allowed in the room where Riodoce employees gathered for security training, days after it was revealed that spyware sold only to governments had been used to monitor journalists and activists in Mexico.
Outside, two policemen were seeking relief from the 100-degree-Fahrenheit [40°C] heat under a tree.
The government assigned them to guard Riodoce's office in a four-story building in a middle-class neighborhood in Culiacan.
Some reporters half-jokingly wondered if these officers were among the 50 percent of police officers labeled untrustworthy by the governor himself.
For months, reporters have been traveling to the mountainous countryside where drug gangs have de facto control.
This week's edition of Riodoce covered three main stories.
One of them was the murder of the brother of former boxing legend Julio Cesar Chavez in Sinaloa.
Plus, they had a tell-all story about spending government money on the governor's hometown.
And just a block from the D.A.'s office, one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants was robbed by a group of people.
There was no official announcement as to who was robbed or how it happened, so one had to be careful when it came time to write what everyone in town knows - the restaurant is a favorite of both drug dealers and law enforcement.
The reporter learned from public records that the restaurant is registered to a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of politics for most of the last century.
Recently, several IRP governors have been accused of corruption in high-profile cases.
Villarreal asked the reporter to write about previous incidents in the same area, including how Guzman's son, nicknamed El Chapo, escaped a military raid.
Just a few months earlier, readers would have looked to Valdez's column for the best source of information on kidnapping.
"Earlier we would have known what happened", said 46-year-old Villarreal, whose slender build has earned him the nickname El Flaco.
"All channels of communication with our sources have now been cut".
Valdez's office has become a repository for signs and stickers protesting the killing of journalists, and the editorial staff has become something they never expected - activists on behalf of the press.
Reporter Miriam Ramirez grabbed a few signs and headed to the district attorney's office the next morning to protest another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared from the western state of Michoacan three days after Valdez's murder.
A burned body has been found, and officials say DNA tests confirm it's his.
Journalists across the country have become more vocal, scrawling "SOS press" on sidewalks and buildings in an organized protest.
On that day, Director Bojorquez is in Washington, D.C., trying to rally international support for justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez's death, Ramirez accused authorities of spying on journalists and killing them for telling the truth.
After that, he asked to be directed away from covering the government, concerned that his anger had affected his objectivity.
Valdez had repeatedly said that Mexican journalists were "confined" by organized crime, complicit government officials and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are killed not only by drug gangs but also by politicians and security forces allied with organized crime.
The media watchdog group Articulo 19 attributed more than half of the attacks on journalists last year to the police and state officials.
"In Mexico, you will die because they want to silence you", Ramirez said.
The murders obviously have a blood-thirsty effect.
No one will forget the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias in the northern border state of Tamaulipas six years ago.
His body was found with a note allegedly signed by the Los Zetas cartel: "I'm here for my reports".
Next to his decapitated head lay a computer keyboard and headphones.
Some publications have decided to close their doors, such as the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua after the murder of its correspondent Miroslava Breach in March.
Others carry on, as did the newspaper El Manana de Nuevo Laredo after the murder of its director in 2004.
In 2010, the newspaper Diario de Ciudad Juarez spoke out against drug cartels with the front-page headline "What Do You Want From Us?"
Some journalists have fled their home states or even the country.
This is a nerve-wracking decision.
In exile, jobs are hard to find, and they still have to patrol the streets to avoid danger.
And sometimes they are persecuted, as is believed to have happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered along with four other women in 2015 in a Mexico City apartment three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay put and keep working have to dance around risky decisions every day.
Ibarra, who once wanted to be a poet, admits that covering the drug trade terrifies him.
"Mexico is going to hell, and that's why I became a reporter", he said.
On a recent Friday at midnight, after the latest issue had been locked up, the editors of Riodoce were sitting on the sidewalk outside their offices, drinking beers, when suddenly everyone's phone began to vibrate.
In the coastal resort city of Mazatlan, 19 people were confirmed dead in gun battles between rival gangs and security forces.
The war continued to escalate, as promised by several cartel messages found in the area.
From that sidewalk, reporters used cell phones to upload the story to the Riodoce website.
The next day, the front page needed a change.
Sirens blared as another shooting took place in the area.
Bojorquez peeked at the officers on duty to see if they were awake.
If they were scared, they didn't show it.
Under a massive portrait of the fallen newspaper founder, with his middle finger visible throughout Sinaloa, Riodoce editors retraced his steps.
"How could I even think about closing", Bojorquez said, "when the day Javier was killed, an intern asked me to send him to cover the streets?"
The dinosaur used protective paint to ward off predators.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, although quite scary.
Scientists have now released the first findings about an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered in a Canadian mine that is so well preserved that experts have described it as the "Mona Lisa of dinosaurs".
It is so well preserved that it was even possible to identify that its armored skin was a reddish-brown color and that its past had been somewhat "complicated".
A report in the journal Current Biology described the creature as "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found" and "one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world".
The fossil is a new species of nodosaur that lived in the mid-Cretaceous period, 110 to 112 million years ago.
Its remarkable preservation stunned researchers, who described it as "truly remarkable".
This armoured herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind ever found, according to National Geographic magazine.
It was found on 21 March 2011 by Shawn Funk while he was mining at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
He spotted something unlike the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
For the next six years, work was done to excavate the animal from the 2,500-pound (1,100-kilogram) plot.
After all this hard work, the final product is finally ready to be presented to the public.
"If you squint a little bit, you can almost believe it's asleep", said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
"This will go down in scientific history as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs".
Examining its skin, scientists found that this herbivore, although covered in armor and resembling a walking tank, was likely threatened significantly by carnivorous dinosaurs.
This heavily armoured dinosaur used red and white paint to hide from predators and a camouflage technique called countershading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This, say experts, allowed the dinosaur to blend in better and avoid predators, since larger dinosaurs were likely hunting it.
This 110-million-year-old creature of the nodosaur family first hit the news in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Scientists have now studied the creature and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli, after Mark Mitchell of the museum's laboratory, who was part of the team that spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly uncovering the animal.
Thanks to the specimen's remarkable preservation, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the shape and size of the scales on the animal's body.
They discovered countershading, a common defense mechanism in the animal kingdom, meaning that the creature's upper half was darker than its lower half.
Although common, the finds come as a surprise, since Borealopelta are much larger than the shelled animals alive today.
This suggests that the dinosaur was being actively hunted by other carnivorous dinosaurs, so evolution favored hiding over confrontation as a survival tactic.
But most modern repellent animals - such as deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and more vulnerable to prey, suggesting that nodosaurs really struggled to survive.
"The aggressive hunting of an enormous and heavily armoured dinosaur shows how dangerous Cretaceous predators could be", said Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the creature for clues to its life, including the preserved contents of its gut to determine what the animal ate for its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried by the current to the sea, where it sank backwards to the ocean floor.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as southern Florida is today, and rivers and oceans likely extended farther inland than they do today.
"This nodosaur is really remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved armoured skin, but it also remains three-dimensional, retaining the original shape of the animal", Brown said.
"As a result, the animal looks much as it did in the Cretaceous period.
It doesn't take much imagination to reconstruct it - all you have to do is squint and it looks as if he were asleep".
The Cretaceous Period was a time when giant, two-legged, meat-eating dinosaurs called theropods roamed the Earth.
Although the king of them all, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been hunted by some of its fearsome predecessors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, a monster 38 feet long and weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose recent findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelta was washed out to sea after death and mummified in mud.
The creature was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk while he was mining at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and scales, and it is intact from the cone to the hips.
These creatures averaged 18 feet (5 meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
Two 20-inch spikes protruded from its shoulders.
Scientists believe that this armoured herbivore roamed across what is now western Canada until a flooded river washed it out to sea.
But the dinosaur's burial under the sea helped preserve its armor in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the bumpy plates of armor along the dinosaur's skull are still covered with skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic magazine: "This level of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more incredible it seems.
Petrified skin still covers the jagged plates of the animal's skull.
The right forefoot rests next to him, and five toes are extended upward.
I can count the number of scales on his feet".
How did one activist find the answer to the question "Whose streets?"
On August 9th, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was in complete shock.
Just one day after arriving in New York City, this St. Louis resident was sitting on her bed in an Airbnb room, surfing Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled upon a post by an old schoolmate.
It said, "An 18-year-old has just been killed by the police and is still lying in the street".
He was confused why no one else had posted this information on his feed, so he closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
The likes of @TheePharoah's posts were repeatedly shared on his timeline.
A rapper from the St. Louis area live-tweeted the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying in the street for four hours.
"This is crazy", Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to him or his community.
She put her phone away, but later that night, she saw another tweet, this time announcing a crowd gathering on Canfield Drive.
Photos were shared of police tape and people screaming and a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a sign that read, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
He was watching a live feed of a police officer standing with a barking dog in front of a group of protesters.
In another video, he said another policeman brandished a gun and shouted: "I'll kill you all... animals".
Ferrell remembers thinking, "This is unusual".
"This isn't the kind of murder we're used to or what we'd call typical".
At that moment, I felt fear.
I was angry and crying".
She booked a return flight and flew home the next day.
After landing at 11:00 p.m., she went to her father's house to pick up her six-year-old daughter and decided that the two of them would drive to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which opens in theaters August 11.
This is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience from the perspective of the people who live in this community and filled the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell and his daughter - wearing a floral dress and a matching crown - drove toward Ferguson, they renewed a conversation they had had many times before that morning - about the black experience and living conditions.
"Remember when I taught you how the black community had to fight for its rights?" he remembers asking himself.
"We're on our way to Ferguson right now because an 18-year-old boy was killed by the police, and it's not right".
"I couldn't not take him with me", Ferrell said later.
"What is happening now is the culmination of what has happened in the past.
He needs to know it and see it and grow up around it.
She needs to learn about activism and organizing, but she also needs to learn about the different layers of black experience and conditioning and what we need to do to break free and liberate ourselves.
Even if I manage to raise her without her personally experiencing blatant racism, she's no different than any other black girl.
I feel I would be doing her a disservice if I protected her from this world".
The first stop they made when they got to Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, across the street from the police station, which had become a kind of campground where activists waited for news of Officer Darren Wilson, who was ultimately not charged.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined forces with a local business owner who made lunches.
They put together food bags and helped distribute them to the protesters.
For Ferrell, a new kind of activism was slowly taking shape.
"My activism completely changed after August 9", she said, noting that when she was a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Nursing Student Association and focused on food rights and health disparities in black communities.
"I had no organizational experience.
It all just worked out".
Weeks later, at an evening rally, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors.
Folayan said that he and cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar simply wanted to document what was happening.
The question in Farrell's mind was, "Are you trying to document what's going on, or are you trying to find a story to exploit?"
Such skepticism was prompted by countless cases of people - often white - coming into a community and trying to profit from its pain and resilience.
In a recent interview, Folayan explained: "We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson were not being heard, and we wanted to do something different".
Folayan had already teamed up with co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism with death row inmates.
His involvement made the project intriguing to Ferrell and six other locals who were followed by the "Whose Streets?" team for years after Brown's shooting.
"In this documentary, no one speaks for us or with us, we speak for ourselves", said Davis.
"It was important to me how these people were portrayed because that's how I was portrayed".
While the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement was not about "a savior leading, but about bringing a community together", as Folayan put it - she emerged as the film's most outspoken participant.
As a result, Whose Streets? documents surprisingly personal aspects of Farrell's life, such as falling in love and marrying his wife.
"I felt like I was naked", said Ferrell, laughing at the first time he saw the finished canvas.
"But I realized that to do this work, to humanize black people, you have to have a certain vulnerability".
More than that, Ferrell's story highlights and re-centers the role of the black lesbian woman in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the #BlackLivesMatter social media movement following the killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 are gay.
"Black lesbians in leadership have generally held the movement back", said Ferrell, "and that's because we have to constantly fight on multiple fronts.
Black homosexual women have to carry the whole burden".
Folayan agreed, noting that "the movement is really kept alive by black women, and many of them are black lesbians".
He claims, however, that "this is not an equal opportunity type of thing" - Ferrell was not chosen to be the focus of the film because of his identity.
"He was a person with the right energy", she said.
"But it's not a coincidence that she was on the front lines, because as a black homosexual woman living in hot spots like this, there's a lot at stake.
His energy can be felt through the screen".
Meanwhile, news cameras have long since disappeared from Ferguson, but race relations between the community and the police remain tenuous.
Ferrell's probation for blocking a highway during a protest is up for another two and a half years.
He describes the socio-political climate in the area he calls home simply as "grass-roots".
However, he still holds dear a mantra that has been etched in his memory since he walked the streets of Ferguson a mere three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our duty to win.
We have to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains".
