A Northwestern professor and an Oxford University employee are wanted on suspicion of murder.
Police say a nationwide manhunt is underway for a Northwestern University professor and an Oxford University employee who have become suspects after the body of a man with fatal stab wounds was found in a Chicago luxury apartment.
According to Cook County court documents, non-bailable warrants were issued Monday for the arrest of 42-year-old Wyndham Latham and 56-year-old Andrew Warren on charges of first-degree murder in connection with the death of Trenton H. James Cornell-Duranleau.
According to court documents, 26-year-old Cornell-Duranleau died from multiple stab wounds.
According to an alert issued to the community by the Chicago Police Department, the body was discovered on July 27.
Officers received a phone call and arrived at the Grand Plaza apartment building to find the victim with multiple stab wounds.
Officials say Cornell-Duranleau was pronounced dead at the scene and investigators are treating the stabbing as a homicide, while police are actively searching for two suspects.
Lathem has been an associate professor of microbiology and immunology at Northwestern University since 2007.
University vice president of public affairs Alan K. Cubbage said in an emailed statement that Lathem has now been suspended and banned from Northwestern University's campus.
"This is now a criminal matter being investigated by the proper authorities and Northwestern University is cooperating with the investigation", Cubbage said.
Warren is a senior lecturer in finance at Oxford University.
A spokesman for the university and Somerville College said in an emailed statement: "We have been in contact with British police and stand ready to assist US investigators in any way we can".
The statement also said that Warren's colleagues are shocked and want him to turn himself in.
Chicago Police Department Communications Director Anthony Guglielmi is urging the suspects to turn themselves in to authorities.
"Police have an idea of where they are, but we are working intensively to determine their exact location", said Guglielmi.
According to Guglielmi, local, regional, and national authorities are helping to search for the suspects.
Guglielmi said the police received a phone call from the manager of the Grand Plaza apartment building who had just received a cryptic tip that something had happened in apartment 1008.
According to police descriptions, it was a gruesome sight.
According to Guglielmi, it is not clear whether the event itself also took place on 27 July.
He said the security cameras confirm Latham and Warren were in the building.
"We believe Professor Latham and the victim were having a relationship", Guglielmi added.
In a letter to residents, the Grand Plaza management stated: "Police are currently working to establish the chronology of events and the victim's background, and are investigating various motives, including the possibility of a domestic dispute".
Startups to help your company avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but the surveys were unproductive.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful, or worse, misleading.
And even though he promised anonymity, some employees didn't trust the process.
"The system just wasn't consistent or objective", said Errett, who runs Madison Reed, a San Francisco-based e-commerce hair-care company with 75 employees.
So he called in outside help.
There's a new breed of human resources start-up emerging that helps companies figure out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software with the explicit goal of measuring employee engagement, they enable companies to conduct snap polls, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and a complaint hotline, and in some cases allow native speakers to bypass C-level executives and go directly to the board.
"Now there are tools like Strava and Fitbit for health tracking, but where is Fitbit for your business?" asked Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint, whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett says that in the three years he has been using Glints, he has gained much insight into what his employees think and feel.
In addition to snap surveys and interviews with specific teams, it offers a corporate heat map that shows which departments have the most complaints and which managers have the lowest support, enabling it to identify the causes.
Companies are starting to realize that they need to keep up with their work culture in order not to become the next Uber, which has been embroiled in scandal since a former employee published a blog post describing a harassing environment that punished those who dared to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the desire for insight is a lucrative business opportunity.
The global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020, according to financial technology statistics website Let's Talk Payments.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, has seen an increase in interest and activity this year in the wake of Uber's questionable reputation.
Convercent has almost 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a client.
Like Glintk, Convercent allows companies to send customized pulse surveys, collect real-time confidential responses, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous hotline for employees to report inappropriate behaviour.
And when the CEO is involved, complaints go straight to the board.
"Public opinion has been hijacked by regulators", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
Quinlan said that if a company is found to treat its employees poorly or behave unethically, the company could face serious consequences, such as consumer boycotts, employee departures and lawsuits, even if regulators do not intervene.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employee awareness of policies and procedures and to provide an easy way to communicate with corporate headquarters.
In the past, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he had to find a phone number or an e-mail address at corporate headquarters, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a daunting and inconvenient process, said Ruby Tuesday general counsel James Vitrano, who said there was no good way to track employee complaints.
But now that the company is using Convercent, problems such as discrimination, harassment or unfair pay practices that previously went unnoticed by managers in offices in other cities or states can be identified and dealt with more quickly.
"I can get closer to the holistic 360-degree experience of employees", said Vitrano, who leads the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
"And we protect our shareholders from lawsuits with employees".
