Glinti received a $10 million investment from Bessemer Venture Partners in November, bringing the company's total funding to $60 million.
Such investments are not surprising given the links between business, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today's workers expect more from their jobs than ever before.
In competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are just bets on the table.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy at a company, feel listened to and that the work they do is fulfilling, they are more committed to the success of the company", said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee experience at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glints.
Investors make money when their portfolio companies do well; companies do well when employees are engaged and involved.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement, it's no wonder they're gaining traction.
Having data on employee involvement is important, say work culture experts.
But this data is useless if the company's supervisors don't do anything with it.
In fact, when a company asks for feedback from its employees, it can create expectations that change is coming.
And if change is not happening fast enough or at all, it can lead to frustration and reduced employee engagement.
"If you ask for 4,000 proposals, you have to be prepared for 4,000 interviews", said Russell Raath, president of Kotter International, a management consulting firm, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
"Because when things don't get done, employees think, 'Did you really listen to me?
Do you care?
