Rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent a draft law amending the Act on the Release of Genetically Modified Organisms into the Environment (GMOVS) and the Plant Protection Act for approval.
The amendment to the Act abolishes the requirement to create a separate database for both the location and the operators of genetically modified (GM) crops, using the Plant Health Register.
In addition, the obligation for the operator of the GM crop to have a prior agreement with a beekeeper within a defined radius is modified.
Although no genetically modified crops are currently grown in Estonia, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and non-modified crops.
This will continue at least until Estonia has decided to declare itself GMO-free", said Sigmar Suu, head of the Plant Health Department at the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
'At the same time, it must be borne in mind that the measures developed must be appropriate and proportionate, taking into account the costs and administrative burden for both the private and public sectors,' Suu added.
The draft law repeals the provisions relating to the location and operator database of GM crops in the GMOVS and handling training, establishes the requirements for handling GM crops and starting economic activity.
Specifically as regards beekeeping, the current obligation for the GM crop grower to inform the beekeeper of the start of cultivation of the GM crop will be replaced by an obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with the beekeeper before the start of cultivation.
The draft law has been sent to the ministries for approval.
All interested parties can consult the draft in the information system and, if they wish, submit their comments to the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
The planned changes will primarily affect persons active in the field of plant breeding, beekeepers and the Agricultural Board.
Only one GM crop, MON 810 maize, is authorised for cultivation in the European Union, including Estonia.
So far, however, no Estonian farmer has shown interest in growing a GM crop.
This is due to the fact that Estonia is free from the European corn borer, a pest to which maize line MON 810 is resistant.
Also, varieties of this maize line have been bred for the southern regions and this maize is not suitable for our climatic conditions.
In order to ascertain the above, the Ministry of Rural Affairs has ordered studies in 2015 and 2016 to detect possible contamination with GM organisms in seeds of different varieties of rapeseed, maize and soybean grown in Estonia.
The results of the analysis of the samples taken showed that the seeds did not contain any foreign genes and the study concluded that the seeds of rapeseed, maize and soybean varieties grown in Estonia do not contain GMOs.
From the above, it can be concluded that no GM crops are intentionally cultivated in Estonia and it was also confirmed that no accidental contamination took place.
