The White House exhibit cost the taxpayers thousands.
According to military documents leaked to TIME magazine, the White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter onto the South Lawn last month for an event celebrating American manufacturing cost taxpayers $24,000.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D, referred to as Marine One when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 White House event showcasing America's construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured industrial products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, built in Connecticut, was displayed with a yacht from Maine, a fire engine from Wisconsin, and a forklift from Mississippi.
According to documents from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the squadron responsible for operating the helicopter, the White House War Cabinet requested the helicopter's presence with a partial order, or FARGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn for an "unusual" event.
"I wanted you to be aware of this because this is an unusually high profile event", the commander of HMX-1 said in an email to his superior, the Navy's Deputy Chief of Naval Operations for Aviation, the day before the event.
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at about 7:15 a.m. for the 7:15 a.m. event and would stay until the yard was cleaned up between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m. that evening.
It added that if the departure from the White House was delayed, another crew would be needed for the return flight due to time constraints.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event and the squadron security team remained close to the aircraft throughout its stay on the ground.
The documents provided to TIME magazine did not say whether a second crew was eventually needed or not.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
The documents show that HMX-1 investigated whether the event might violate this provision.
"We asked if it violated the Hatch Act, and we were told it did not", the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have a choice", replied the deputy commanding officer.
The White House declared the event an official "Made in America" event and would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president endorsed the Senate's health care reform effort and praised efforts to rein in government regulations.
The use of an aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for political gain is not new.
Presidents have to use them to travel.
But the requirement to use them purely for a photo shoot is unusual.
Trump gained attention in February when his presidential plane rolled into the background at his first campaign event in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of messages complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is very pleased with the 'Made in America' exhibit, which featured products from all 50 states made with American materials by American workers", said Acting White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often make test flights around Washington and the South Lawn to practice landing the President of the United States at the White House with centimeter precision.
While Trump was in Germany for the G20 summit in early July, HMX-1 made 58 test landings on the White House lawn.
According to the official, the flight to the "Made in America" event was part of the crew's normal training for the month.
The squadron's helicopters flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidential support missions".
According to the White House, none of the other exhibits at the event ever put a dent in the taxpayer's pocket.
According to a Sikorsky representative, the company was not involved in the organisation of the display on the southern apron of the helicopter.
HMX-1 doesn't keep budget documents for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the event is difficult to determine.
But according to the DOD's FY 2017 hourly rates, the VH-3D compensation rate is $24,380 per flight hour.
The squadron's flight logs indicated a flight time of 30 minutes each way from its home base at Marine Corps Air Station Quantico, Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is far less than that amount.
"Calculating the cost to taxpayers on the basis of estimated reimbursement rates is highly misleading", said Walters.
'These estimated reimbursement rates include staff, maintenance and a number of other irreversible costs taken into account in the annual appropriations.'
According to the 2015 RAND study, the Department of Defense's reimbursement rates do not include personnel costs, but do cover fuel, maintenance, and contract-related costs.
Former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter at the time.
"The point is to show things made in America this week", Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud that they contribute to our national security and that there are probably hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I believe that, like most Americans, we are all proud of this helicopter and the other military equipment that so many Americans have worked so tirelessly to build.
So, of course, it's right to point that out".
It's unclear whether or not Trump collided with the helicopter as he toured the South Lawn for the event, but he was behind the wheel of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives, poking fun at the company's products on his personal fleet of aircraft to the media.
"I know Sikorsky very well", said the president, "I have three of their products".
