An alcohol that, when consumed, is equivalent to a brain workout.
Livestrong reports that Dr. Gordon Shepherd is such a big fan of wine that he believes it exercises the brain better than anything else in the world.
Shepherd is a neuroscientist at Yale.
He was referring, not to alcohol or its effect on our emotions and thoughts, but to the "very active" process of tasting wine.
As we sniff the glass, swirl the wine, savor it, and savor the aftertaste, we engage our brain to create the taste of wine.
According to Shepherd, the molecules in wine don't actually contain flavor, but flavor comes from the way wine stimulates the brain.
He uses the analogy of how the brain "sees" color.
"Taste is not in the wine, but in the taster", says Sheperd.
Other factors that affect the taste of wine include our age, gender, and even the amount of saliva we produce.
Of course, Shepherd cautions that wine is not for getting drunk on.
"There's got to be more to it", he says.
If you take too big a sip, the system is overloaded.
According to a 2004 study, people who drink more than three glasses of wine a day risk memory loss, loss of balance, and decreased mental function.
10% of employees in the Estonian ICT sector are paid less than their colleagues
Data from the recruitment company Fontes reveals that 10% of employees in the Estonian ICT sector are paid less than their colleagues.
There is a 10 percent pay gap between men and women, reports the portal Geenius.
The Fontese ICT sector wage survey covered 59 IT and telecommunications companies.
A total of 8 577 posts were examined.
63% of the posts were held by men.
"Although only 3 companies stated that the pay gap is in favour of men and the remaining companies believe that there is no pay gap, in reality, when comparing similar jobs, men's basic monthly earnings are on average 10% higher than women's and men's total annual earnings are on average 8% higher than women's", said Ilmar Põhjala, an analyst at Fontes.
