According to the UN, Afghan democracy depends on the role of women in politics.
The head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said Wednesday that elections can only be representative of the people if all members of society, including women, play a role.
Nicholas Haysom, head of the UN Assistance Mission, said that hundreds of women are running for local council elections, three women are running for vice president, and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
"The importance of the role of women cannot be overstated", he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are involved at all stages of the electoral process.
Local and presidential elections will be held in Afghanistan on 5 April.
The Taliban, for their part, have threatened an electoral process that would coincide with a transitional period during which international military operations would have an advisory role.
This year's elections mark the first peaceful transfer of power from one democratically elected government to the next.
According to Haysom, the strong role of women will increase the success of democracy in Afghanistan.
According to the Independent Election Commission of Afghanistan, 1.2 million of the 3.6 million registered voters are women.
