From the Philippines to the World - The Shoulder Bag's Journey to the Heart of Fashion
The straw bag is a summer classic that has become a hit in its own right in recent years, a must-have for any true summertime lover, and despite its humble origins, merchants have managed to weld a price tag to match.
A straw bag is probably one of those things that everyone has owned at least once in his life and that does not arouse any particular emotion in him.
It's just there, and if it's not there, it's not broken.
Now, however, shoulder bags are making a real comeback, and fashionistas have traded their elegant designer bags for simple straw-woven bags for the summer months.
Not only is it a beach bag but today it is also popular as a street bag and is even worn to the office by more adventurous women.
At this point, though, it's worth considering whether your boss would prefer a summer look or a more formal look with a notepad and a laptop.
Variety, however, has made shoulder bags a summertime favorite for women.
For example, if you read foreign fashion blogs, one of the first things you'll notice is that when a fashionista goes on vacation, the first thing they do is go to the local market and buy a shoulder bag that they'll wear for the rest of their vacation, to the beach, to the market, to hang out with their girlfriends.
Some bloggers are so generous that they buy large quantities of bags from the market and sell or give them away to their loyal readers.
Interestingly, the demand for handbags among readers is so great that in the real world, women (and men!) would probably be throwing their arms around each other to win one.
In some ways, this craze is understandable, since it is rare in the fashion world to be able to buy a hit item for just a few dollars.
Of course, shrewd merchants have also discovered an easy way to make money, with high-end brands selling straw bags for hundreds or even thousands of dollars.
Probably so the wealthier customers don't have to feel like mere mortals walking around with cheap bags.
For example, you can buy a Dolce & Gabbana straw bag that costs more than a thousand euros.
However, the interpretation of a Chanel shoulder bag can cost up to 6,000 euros.
Unlike most mohawks, however, the origins of the shoulder bag go back much further than that.
In fact, it is said that the origins of the rucksack lie far away in the Philippines, from where it spread around the world.
The weaving of straw sacks is primarily an export trade, and locals are not often seen carrying them around.
The technique is said to date back to the 14th century and is quite similar to regular basket weaving.
Since straw bags do not have to be woven as tightly as baskets, they can be woven with patterns and other materials that add personality and appeal.
For example, in recent years, bags embroidered with colored ribbons or leather have become very fashionable.
But the shoulder bags can thank actress Jane Birkin most of all, who has never been a bigger fan of knitted shoulder bags.
In fact, she matched the straw bag to all sorts of outfits and didn't even have to wear it to the Cannes Film Festival.
Not the least of the reasons for their popularity today is that they are easy to care for and, unlike all other types of pocket gophers, do not require special care, being washed off with water and a wet towel.
As is often the case with trends, brands have come up with all sorts of interpretations besides the classic look.
For example, if you wish, you can have a silk scarf made of straw or a small shoulder bag.
However, it is good to remember that the classic straw bag will never go out of style, but the straw mat will.
So, what's a classic straw bag?
For centuries, a woven straw sack, similar in style to a basket, with an open top and short, strawlike heels, has been considered a classic.
Five healthy ice creams that are surprisingly easy to make at home
Lifehack.org has come up with ways to make different kinds of ice cream at home that contain fewer calories than store-bought ice cream.
Lemon ice cream - In a large bowl, whisk together the lemon juice and sugar, add the buttermilk and whipped cream, and blend to a smooth paste.
Chocolate and peanut butter ice cream - Blend together Greek yogurt, frozen bananas, cocoa powder and maple syrup to form a homogeneous mass.
Then add a little peanut butter and blend the mixture for a few seconds.
The ice cream's almost ready.
Peach ice cream - Mix skimmed milk, sugar substitute, egg, frozen or plain peach slices, and almond extract in a bowl until a uniform mass is obtained, and place the mixture in the refrigerator to thaw.
Coconut ice cream - Blend coconut milk, coconut flakes, vanilla extract, maple syrup, and frozen bananas and place the mixture in the refrigerator.
Banana ice cream - Mix frozen banana pieces in a bowl with skimmed milk to a smooth paste, serve with walnuts, and eat immediately.
