GMB is concerned about investment in McVitie's Glasgow plant
The union is seeking confirmation from the managers of biscuit maker McVitie's about long-term production plans at the company's Glasgow plant.
According to GMB Scotland, it has remained silent on the future of the investment in the Tollcross site.
The factory, which produces Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies and other products, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie's, said they've invested more than £5 million in the facility over the last few years.
Additional workers were hired, and union leaders "are the first to know" when there is a change in operations.
In a letter to the site manager, GMB Scotland asked McVitie's to 'address concerns that funding is not being used to modernise production lines'.
Senior GMB organiser Drew Duffy said: "The fact that we are not getting clarity from the site manager on Tollcross's business needs and future investment plan is of deep concern to our members.
Several generations of families have worked here and the workforce is largely made up of people from the local community and the Glasgow area, an essential pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social exclusion.
Therefore, in terms of jobs, wages and welfare, and in the context of Brexit, the rising cost of living and the chronic decline in production, the east end of Glasgow desperately needs a fast-growing operation in McVitie'.
A spokesman for Plaidis said: 'The site manager at the Toll Crossing only received a letter from GMB Scotland yesterday and the company is responding directly as we value active communication with staff and union representatives.
Two months ago, there was a regular meeting at Tollcross between workers and GMB representatives where a number of issues were openly discussed.
At that time, we discussed with our employees that, like any other company operating in a highly competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are reviewing our operations on an ongoing basis - and this applies to all of our businesses and facilities - to ensure that we remain competitive.
He added: 'Over the last few years we have invested over £5 million in the Tollcross site, much of it in production lines and improvements to operations.
We fully understand the legacy of Tollcross as a manufacturing facility, and should there be any changes to the operations of the facility, employees and union representatives will be the first to know".
Did PSG warn Barcelona three years ago about approaching Neymar?
La Liga may regret their interest in Marco Verratti.
Paris Saint-Germain are not giving up on Neymar with a £189m bid, but did they warn Barcelona three years ago about their record-breaking campaign?
This high-profile approach has opened up the summer transfer window and the Ligue 1 club are set to more than double the current world record for overtaking set last season by Paul Pogba's return to Manchester United for £89 million.
Once the transfer is completed, Neymar will become the world's most expensive player and also the highest paid professional athlete in the world, earning an after-tax salary of over £500,000 per week from PSG.
Barcelona are understandably angry about both the approach and Neymar's release, although a source close to the Catalan board confirms that the club has always taken the best care of the footballer since his arrival from Santos in 2013.
But did the president of PSG warn the football world of this possibility three years ago?
When Manchester City showed interest in signing Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi issued a stern warning to any club thinking of signing one of PSG's best players.
"I am not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, we will confront them and contact those players", Al-Khelaifi said.
"We respect all clubs.
But if they try to sign one of our players, they have to face the consequences".
Barcelona appear to have crossed that line, as the Spanish club showed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG made it clear that they would not allow the Italian to leave under any circumstances and that Barcelona could suffer a setback as a result of this interest, losing one of their prized assets in the form of Neymar.
Prime Minister: Ireland wants to build bridges, not borders, after Brexit
'Brexit seriously threatens to drive a wedge between Northern Ireland and Ireland, Great Britain and Ireland,' Varadkar warned during his first visit to Northern Ireland since taking office in June.
"I can't imagine who would benefit", he added.
Cross-border infrastructure projects made possible today's free movement of people and goods, Varadkar said.
"This is our vision for the future: building bridges, not borders", he stressed.
Mr Varadkar said he would prefer Britain to remain part of the European Union and, since it could not, to remain part of the European single market.
This would maintain the current free trade between the Republic of Ireland and the United Kingdom.
Another way to make the UK's departure smoother would be to create a customs union between the EU and the UK, explained the Irish Prime Minister.
Noting that such an agreement existed with Turkey, Varadkar said: "We could certainly have one with the UK".
The alternative would be a return to the customs posts, which would herald a historic split and political failure.
"An obstacle to trade, prosperity and peace", said the Irish prime minister.
He called Brexit 'the challenge of our generation' and warned that its outcome could affect every aspect of daily life in Northern Ireland.
The Irish Prime Minister met the leaders of the main parties in Northern Ireland during his visit to Belfast.
Märt Avandi, who has completed his first half-distance triathlon:
Today, the winter capital of Otepää hosted the largest triathlon festival in the Baltic States, with about a thousand triathletes from over thirty countries taking part in the half-Ironman race.
The 70.3-mile distance consisted of 1.2 miles (1.9 km) of swimming, 55 miles (90 km) of cycling, and 13.2 miles (21.1 km) of cycling.
Among others, Märt Avandi finished his first triathlon victoriously.
"I thought it was going to be difficult, and it turned out to be difficult", admitted Avandi at the finish.
Despite its complexity, Avandi found that the triathlon is actually accessible to almost everyone.
"It's not the distance that kills, it's the pace", he said, implying that almost anyone can finish at a reasonable pace.
Except for Ott Sepp: "Ott is good at physics, but he can't swim".
Avanti had been training hard since February.
Four or five hours a week at first, then ten.
With a time of 5:34:12, he finished 270th overall.
Although Avandi lost to both Raio Piiro (time 04:59:53) and Jürgen Lig (time 05:06:37), he beat other competitors in the so-called "celebrity class".
Tanel Padar, who was a "good role model" last year, lost to Avandi by seven minutes (time 05:41:54), journalist Sten Teppan by 16 minutes (time 05:50:23), Kalev Kruus and Raivo E. Tamm by about an hour (times 06:31:53 and 06:45:18).
German Johannes Moldan was crowned overall winner of the men's Otepää stage of the Ironman series with a time of 3:58:27, the best of the Estonians was Ivo Suur with a time of 04:14:09.
The women's race was won by Helle Frederiksen of Denmark with a time of 04:24:01, while Maria Jänese of Estonia, who lost almost half an hour to Frederiksen, finished with a time of 04:58:58.
Avandi swam a distance of 1.9 km in 42 minutes and 14 seconds.
